[normal]R (Husain) v ASA and SSHD
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2001] EWHC Admin 852
[normal]Asylum-seeker arguing that the ASA was not an independent tribunal so as to comply with ECHR Art 6. Found that asylum support was a ‘civil right’ within 
[normal]the meaning of Art 6 but that the Tribunal was sufficiently independent.  Also found that the withdrawal of support could interfere with Art 3 rights.  JR partially successful
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]yes
[normal]R (SSHD) v ASA  (
[normal]Berkadle
[normal], 
[normal]Perera
[normal] not represented )
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2001] EWHC 811
[normal]SSHD 
[normal]challenging 2 ASA decisions, which had found in favour of the applicants on levels of support, and comparing them to income support levels.  JR successful
[normal]Yes
[normal]R (SSHD) v Chief ASA (
[normal]Dogan
[normal], interested party)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2002] EWHC 2218 
[normal]SSHD challenging decision that
[normal] termination of support for refusal to take up accommodation in the dispersal area was within their jurisdiction. JR successful, and confirmed by the Court of Appeal
[normal]Yes
[normal]R (SSHD) v Chief ASA (
[normal]Manzana
[normal] not represented)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2003] EWHC 269
[normal]SSHD challenging ASA 
[normal]decision on significant, but technical, procedural issue. JR successful
[normal]Yes
[normal]R (
[normal]Rasul
[normal]) v ASA and SSHD
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2006] EWHC 435
[normal]Failed asylum-seeker had been receiving s4 support on basis of no safe route of return to his home town of Kirkuk, Iraq.  SSHD then decid
[normal]ed there was a safe route, so he no longer qualified under (c) and instead needed to show he was taking all reasonable steps (a).  Issue was whether the Tribunal could consider for itself issue of whether safe route of return, or, alternatively, allow appe
[normal]al if SSHD’s opinion (that is safe) is unlawful on 
[normal]Wednesbury
[normal] grounds.  ASA and SSHD both took view that the ASA did not have the jurisdiction to look behind the SSHD’s opinion, and were found to be right. 
[normal]Para 26 as to the ‘availability of judicial review
[normal] in which the correctness in public law terms of the holding by the S of S of a particular opinion may be tested’ precludes the ASA having to do this. 
[normal]But clarified that ASA can substitute its view regarding (a).  Secondary issue as to whether a route of r
[normal]eturn is safe can be considered under (a), this was left open, but otherwise the JR failed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]No
[normal]R (SSHD) v ASA (
[normal]Osman
[normal] and 3 others as interested parties)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2006] EWHC 1248
[normal]SSHD challen
[normal]ging 4 decisions on test under Reg
[normal]3(2)(b) – whether failed asylum 
[normal]seeker ‘unable to travel’- which it viewed as overly generous, and 
[normal]regs
[normal] misconstrued.   JR successful, but test set out not totally unfavourable to asylum seekers
[normal]No 
