[normal]R (
[normal]Anufrijeva
[normal]) v SSHD
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2003] UKHL 36
[normal]For the
[normal] purposes of support, an asylum claim is not determined until the individual has been notified by the Home Office
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]No – subject matter of proceedings
[normal]R (
[normal]Nigatu
[normal]) v SSHD
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2004] EWHC 1806
[normal]Issue of what counts as fresh claim so as to trigger entitlement to 
[normal]support (so crucial to the proposals as the same ‘threshold’ is being used to decide entitlement to legal aid, 3.58). By time of full hearing of JR took place, the SSHD had accepted it as a fresh claim but Mr Justice Collins decided issue of importance so 
[normal]should proc
[normal]eed.  N 
[normal]had attempted to apply for support, but NASS refused it although they acknowledged that the HO had received his fresh claim (applications for s4 support prior to 2005 did not lead to an appeal and so JR was the only remedy here).  Judgme
[normal]nt quotes Bingham in CA in 
[normal]Onibiyo
[normal] 1996 on why the Refugee Convention must allow for fresh claims, and what test should be to qualify as one (new material etc) and that if it is a fresh claim, then there must be a right of appeal. And that JR is the correc
[normal]t remedy to use to compel the SSHD, if he errs, to accept it as a fresh claim. But therefore making a fresh claim and it being accepted as one are 2 separate stages, and only the latter triggers entitlement to s95 support
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Unclear
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Case contains essential 
[normal]guidance to both sides on when a ‘fresh claim’ is made, and therefore when asylum support (s95 or s4) becomes available.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Although there will now be legal aid to make a fresh claim, it is unclear as to whether there will be legal aid for the same asylum se
[normal]eker for an asylum support law case 
[normal]R (
[normal]Erdogan
[normal]) v SSHD
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2004] EWCA 
[normal]Civ
[normal] 1087
[normal]&#xa0;
