[normal]allowed the SSHD’s appeal.  Useful guidance on purpose of the asylum support system, and mechanisms to prevent it being abused (
[normal]para
[normal] 19), and also on the importance of the ‘supervisory role of the court in judicial review to give protection where necessary
[normal]’ (
[normal]para
[normal] 20)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Unclear, as above
[normal]R (
[normal]Limbuela
[normal], 
[normal]Tesema
[normal] and Adam) v SSHD
[normal]Shelter as intervener
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][2006] UKHL 66
[normal]IAA 1999 s55 preventing asylum support from those who did not claim on arrival.  All 5 law lords dismissed the SSHD’s appeal, and confirmed that 
[normal]this was a breach or Art 3. The SSHD had also lost at the High Court stage
[normal]Yes
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BUT[bold] the implication of 3.57 is that they will lose legal aid if they are refused asylum, even for an ongoing case.  Therefore this test case would never have reached the lords.
